/*
 =====================================================
 DVSM META SYSTEM ADDENDUM — EXECUTION GAP ANALYSIS
 =====================================================

 This document describes the DVSM system as a
 structurally valid execution graph, aligned with the
 Reality-Stable Monolith (Bit-Block + Law + Commit Gate).

 It does NOT redefine the kernel.

 It only formalizes execution timing, concurrency,
 and side-channel separation required for production use.
 -----------------------------------------------------
 0. ALIGNMENT WITH DVSM CORE (IMPORTANT)
 -----------------------------------------------------

 This model assumes the finalized DVSMCore architecture:

   STATE MODEL:
     DVSMBitBlock (Pinned Memory)

   TRANSITION MODEL:
     DVSMLaw.propose (Pure Function)

   AUTHORITY MODEL:
     Single Commit Gate (only mutator)

   OBSERVATION MODEL:
     SHA256(State.bytes)

   SIDE CHANNELS:
     Observability / Persistence / Consensus (async only)

 -----------------------------------------------------
 1. WHAT IS CURRENTLY CORRECT
 -----------------------------------------------------

 The pipeline decomposition:

 INPUT → INGEST → AUTHOR → CORE → SECURITY
       → CONSENSUS → PERSISTENCE → OBSERVABILITY

 correctly separates concerns into:

 ✔ Input normalization (Ingest)
 ✔ Identity / provenance tagging (Author)
 ✔ Deterministic state evolution (Core Kernel)
 ✔ Integrity enforcement (Security constraints)
 ✔ Distributed agreement (Consensus layer)
 ✔ Durable storage (Persistence)
 ✔ Non-invasive introspection (Observability)

 This is architecturally consistent with DVSM Core.

 -----------------------------------------------------
 2. EXECUTION MODEL CORRECTION (CRITICAL FIX)
 -----------------------------------------------------

 The original representation implies:

   ❌ strict sequential stage execution

 In DVSM Reality-Stable design, execution is instead:

   ✔ tick-based streaming pulse
   ✔ overlapping concurrent side-channels
   ✔ single-threaded authority kernel

 Correct model:

   INPUT → PULSE TICK → CORE KERNEL → COMMIT
                              ↓
                 side-channels (async fan-out)

 -----------------------------------------------------
 3. WHAT IS NOT EXECUTION-ACCURATE
 -----------------------------------------------------

 (a) Linear pipeline assumption

   ❌ implies stage-by-stage blocking flow
   ✔ actual system is a single atomic tick:

        Pulse(i):
          ingest → propose → commit → emit

------------------------------------------------------

 (b) Security as post-processing gate

   ❌ late validation after mutation
   ✔ correct model:

        Security is split:

        - pre-commit validation (hard constraint)
        - post-commit verification (audit only)

------------------------------------------------------

 (c) Consensus in execution path

   ❌ implied synchronous participation in kernel
   ✔ correct model:

        Consensus is ALWAYS asynchronous
        and cannot block commit.

------------------------------------------------------

 (d) Observability as passive layer

   ✔ correct, but must be explicitly:
        non-blocking + speculative

------------------------------------------------------
 4. MISSING EXECUTION BEHAVIORS (REAL SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS)
------------------------------------------------------

 To make DVSM runtime-stable under load:

 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 • BACKPRESSURE CONTROL (REQUIRED)
 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 Prevents ingest from exceeding kernel tick rate.

 Kernel remains constant-time:
   O(1) per Pulse

------------------------------------------------------

 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 • STREAMING PULSE MODEL (CORE SHIFT)
 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 Replace "pipeline" with:

   DVSM Pulse = atomic state transition event

------------------------------------------------------

 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 • ASYNC SIDE-CHANNEL DISPATCH
 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 These MUST NEVER block commit:

   - Persistence
   - Observability
   - Consensus

------------------------------------------------------

 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 • TEMPORAL DECOUPLING LAYER
 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
 Prevents output-feedback loops:

   Output(t) → does NOT affect Input(t)

   Only affects Input(t + 1) via controlled ingest buffer

------------------------------------------------------

 5. REQUIRED ARCHITECTURAL SHIFT
 -----------------------------------------------------

 OLD MODEL:
   Layered sequential pipeline

 NEW MODEL:
   Single-core deterministic pulse engine

 Execution form:

   Pulse:
     1. Normalize input
     2. Law proposes state
     3. Commit gate writes memory
     4. Hash is emitted
     5. Side channels observe asynchronously

------------------------------------------------------

 6. CORE CONSISTENCY GUARANTEE
------------------------------------------------------

 DVSM remains:

 ✔ Deterministic in structure
 ✔ Stable in memory representation
 ✔ Causal in sequencing
 ✔ Non-blocking in side systems

 BUT:

 ✖ Not globally time-synchronous across nodes
 ✖ Not arithmetic-identical across hardware (FMA variance acknowledged)

------------------------------------------------------

 7. FINAL INTERPRETATION
------------------------------------------------------

 This architecture is:

 ✔ structurally complete
 ✔ execution-consistent
 ✔ concurrency-safe (via separation model)

 It is NOT:

 ✖ a strict pipeline system
 ✖ a fully synchronous distributed machine
 ✖ a zero-drift numerical system

------------------------------------------------------

 SUMMARY

 DVSM is best understood as:

   "a deterministic memory engine with asynchronous
    observational extensions"

 not as a linear compute pipeline.

=====================================================
*/
